###How to fix the Common Vulnerabilities issue of CVE-2017-17382 in nginx web server and which owasp top 10 web 2021 category this issue belong to ?
CVE-2017-17382 is a remote code execution (RCE) vulnerability in the Nginx web server. It is caused by improper input validation in the Nginx configuration file. An attacker could exploit this vulnerability by sending a specially crafted HTTP request to the Nginx server. If the request is successful, the attacker could execute arbitrary code on the server.

To fix this vulnerability, you can apply the following mitigations:

* **Upgrade to Nginx 1.13.10 or higher.** This version of Nginx includes a fix for CVE-2017-17382.
* **Use a web application firewall (WAF).** A WAF can help to filter out malicious HTTP requests and protect your Nginx server from attack.
* **Validate all user input before processing it.** This will help to prevent attackers from injecting malicious code into your Nginx configuration file.
* **Use a content security policy (CSP).** A CSP can help to restrict the types of scripts that can be executed on your web server.

CVE-2017-17382 belongs to the **Injection** category of the OWASP Top 10 Web Application Security Risks 2021.

Here are some additional tips for preventing injection attacks:

* Use a prepared statement when querying a database. This will help to prevent SQL injection attacks.
* Escape all user input before displaying it on a web page. This will help to prevent XSS attacks.
* Use a web application firewall (WAF) to filter out malicious HTTP requests.
* Keep your software up to date. Software vendors regularly release patches to fix security vulnerabilities.

